This page covers the **range and domain of quadratic polynomial models**, specifically showing how to find the minimum or maximum output value a curved fit can produce based on its coefficients. Engineers use this to determine the practical limits of what a quadratic equation can actually achieve—like finding the lowest possible temperature a process can reach or the highest stress a material will experience under the fitted model. You might also search for "vertex of a parabola," "extremum of a quadratic function," "turning point," "maximum/minimum value of a curve," or "output bounds of a fitted model."

\( \displaystyle
\left\{
\begin{array}{ll}
\left(-\infty, \ \beta_0-\frac{\beta_1^2}{4\beta_2}\right] & \mbox{for $\beta_2 < 0$} \\
& \\
\left[\beta_0-\frac{\beta_1^2}{4\beta_2}, \ \infty\right) & \mbox{for $\beta_2 > 0$}
\end{array}
\right. \)
